{
  "text": "The first stage of devolatilization shows that a higher amount of volatile was released during the experiment than the calculated amount. However, the second stage shows lower experimental volatile release; therefore, a higher amount of char compared with the calculated curve was observed. It has been reported that the nitrogen-containing compounds in PU can contribute to acceleration of PVC dehydrochlorization [CITATION_1] , which can explain the higher rate of devolatilization observed in the initial stage of devolatilization. The experimental rate shows a lower rate in the second devolatilization stage, which is probably related to a change in the extent of crosslinking reaction. Despite the assumption that PE would not interact with the other plastics, addition of PE to binary mixture of PU/PVC led to an observed difference between the calculated and experimental curves. This indicates a possible further interaction between PE and binary mixture.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "96544814"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "96544814": {
      "title": "Kinetics of thermal degradation of poly(vinyl chloride)-polyurethane blends",
      "abstract": "Kinetics of thermal degradation of PVC blends with thermoplastic polyurethane in the form of powders and films was investigated. Kinetic equations are proposed for dehydrochlorination of stabilized and non-stabilized blends. Effective rate constants of PVC dehydrochlorination catalysed by urethane groups and their complexes with hydrogen chloride, the rate constants of decomposition and formation of these complexes were calculated."
    }
  }
}